It is not certain when specific acupuncture points were introduced, but the autobiography of Bian Que from around 400–500 BC references inserting needles at designated areas.[31] Bian Que believed there was a single acupuncture point at the top of one's skull that he called the point "of the hundred meetings."[31]:83 Texts dated to be from 156–186 BC document early beliefs in channels of life force energy called meridians that would later be an element in early acupuncture beliefs.[272]
